sex, gender, and sexuality as they did, and especially how the material conformation of hermaphroditic bodies--when combined with social exigencies--forced peculiar constructions. Throughout the book Dreger indicates how this history can help us to understand present-day conceptualizations of sex, gender, and sexuality. This leads to an epilogue, where the author discusses and questions the protocols employed today in the treatment of intersexuals (people born hermaphroditic). Given the history she has recounted, should these protocols be reconsidered and revised? A meticulously researched account of a fascinating problem in the history of medicine, this book will compel the attention of historians, physicians, medical ethicists, intersexuals themselves, and anyone interested in the meanings and foundations of sexual identity.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 31. Jan 2022) 0aIntersexualityxPsychological aspects. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentxHistoryx19th centuryxFrance. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentxHistoryx19th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentxHistoryx20th centuryxFrance. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentxHistoryx20th centuryxGreat Britain. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentxUnited States. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentzFrancexHistoryy19th century. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentzFrancexHistoryy20th century. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentzGreat BritainxHistoryy19th century. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentzGreat BritainxHistoryy20th century. 0aIntersexualityxTreatmentzUnited States. 0aSex (Psychology). 7aMEDICAL / History.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertHUP eBook Package Archive 1893-1999z978311044221240uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780674034334423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780674034334/original  a978-3-11-044221-2  HUP eBook Package A